column169: Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 1ft-by-1ft area and 2ft-by-2ft area of asphalt and a 10ft-by-3ft area of the trailer floor. They estimated that one (1) gallon of material was released most likely due to a forklift puncturing one (1) 55-gallon metal drum. Clean Harbors personnel inspected all 24 drums on the trailer and found only one (1) drum was affected. The damaged 55-gallon metal drum was contained in one (1) 85-gallon metal drum. Contractor personnel deployed granular absorbents to the affected areas and containerized them into one (1) 55-gallon metal drum. The generated waste was staged onsite and will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column169: ABF Supervisor states that checker Emzer Caston was loading trailer 504741 when his rear tire slipped on a dock bumper and pushed him forward into a shipment of UN3082, ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID, N.O.S. (POLYAMINE RESIN), 9, PG III, MARINE POLLUTANT which completely punctured the 5 5 gallon drum and is actively spilling from the trailer onto the yard. ABF Supervisor states that about 20 gallons or so has spilled into the yard and that rain is in the forecast around 11PM (EST) tonight for Atlanta. Safety advised to block off the premise of the spill and try their best to stop t he spill from entering any drains. ABF Supervisor states that deployed snakes to stop the spill from spreading on the yard. Safety contacted CURA and they're dispatching a cleanup crew on emergency response to the terminal. FCE personnel collected two (2) damaged 55-gallon drums and placed in two (2 ) overpacks for disposal. Crews then deployed granular absorbent to the impacted trailer floor and concrete yard beneath the trailer and worked them in utilizing hand tools. Once collected, FCE personnel utilized a cleaning agent and absorbent pads to collect any residual product from the impacted s urfaces. All UN3082 impacted material was collected and containerized in two (2)55-gallon drums and ABF personnel took possession of the waste for terminal disposal. FCE personnel noted no further actions required on-site and crews demobilized.

On February 12, 2025, at 0846 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Ranger personnel in Troy, MO regarding a vehicle accident that impacted several cargo products.  Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors found (1) 330-gallon tote of Chlorite solution (UN1908, 8, III), (47) 15-gallon drums of Sodium bisulfate (UN2837, 8, III), and 456 gallons of Citric acid and Copper sulfate pentahydrate (UN1760, 8, III) to be damaged but not leaking. The release was reportedly due to a trailer fire, impacting asphalt and soil. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The release was cleaned up with absorbents and the proper PPE. All impacted soil was excavated and backfilled. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (19) roll-offs, (1) 330-gallon tote, and (1) 55-gallon DM which were taken offsite by the contractor for proper disposal. On April 23, 2025, approximately 430 gallons of recovered Sodium bisulfate was transferred into 2 totes. There was 705 gallons of Sodium bisulfate on the BOL - so up to 275 gallons of pH Safe was released or solidified and that is what is included on this report. Again, the confirmed spilled amount of this material was not discovered until April 23, 2025, which is why it is now be reported.

THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CONTAINMENT WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 275 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column169: Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 10 square foot area of concrete dock floor and estimated that seventy-five (75) gallons of material was released due to a puncture from a skid damaging one (1) 270-gallon IBC poly tote. Clean Harbors personnel used gravity feed to complete a tote transfer from the damaged IBC poly tote to one (1) 250-gallon IBC poly tote. Contractor personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area. The absorbents, cut up tote, rags, and PPE were all containerized. One (1) 55-gallon metal drum contains approximately 45 gallons of product and granular absorbents. One (1) superstack contains cut up poly tote, spent oil dri, rags, and PPE. One (1) 250-gallon IBC poly tote contains transferred material. Before demobilization, the generated waste was staged onsite, and Dayton Freight approved of the cleanup. The generated waste will remain onsite for the Dayton Freight Lines team to coordinate disposal

column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a leaking plastic tote containing hazardous product, Trimeta Boost. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimate 1-cup release onto the top of the plastic tote in a 2’ x 2’ area as a result of a lose / faulty cap. The contractor replaced the broken cap with a new cap and performed a slosh test to ensure that no further leakage would occur in transit. No waste was generated from this response and the tote will ship on to the Consignee. No soil, storm-drains, or waterways were impacted by this incident.

Once cured, the pail was placed in an overpack drum in preparation for disposition.

column169: The leaking container was picked up by Veolia from a customer on 4/2/25 and transporter to the Veolia 10 Day In-Transit facility located at 3100 Hedley Street, Philadelphia, PA 19137. The container was offloaded with other containers and placed on another transport vehicle the afternoon of 4/2/25. The following day, the container was inspected and was not observed to be leaking. On 4/4/25 during a routine inspection of the site, the container was determined to be leaking as a small wet area was observed around the circumference of the bottom of the container. The container was placed in a salvage drum, and the area decontaminated. The leak was caused most likely by potential damage to the container or a leaking seam in the plastic.

column169: On 4/12/2025 at approximately 0350, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 4155356 at the ramp facility in Anchorage, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of 7 containers of acrylic paint packaged in a fiberboard box.  The shipment emitted a urethane odor, requiring further inspection, searching for a potential leak.  While no contents leaked, the inspection did result in the discovery of undeclared paint.  The accompanying safety data sheet classified the commodity as nonregulated, which does not appear to be correct.  The shipment is being held, pending an investigation by the FAA.

column43: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column169: On April 16, 2025, Hub personnel reported that unit RNLU 100108 was leaking a blue liquid that had seeped through the container floor, resulting in a  spill of less than 1 gallon of product onto the ground. An interior inspection of the cargo inside revealed a mixed load of hazardous materials palletized and  (Printer Ink) in 55   gallon drum on the floor of the container towards the rear of the container. The pallets were stowed two rows wide, stacked two high.  The load was secured using a 4x4   foot piece of lumber nailed into a 40"x48" pallet at the rear of the container.  A 55   gallon drum containing printer ink, classified as a Class 3 Flammable Hazardous Material, was discovered leaking inside a container positioned on  railcar FEC 72198. Upon inspection, it was determined that approximately 25 gallons of ink had been released inside the container and onto the interior  of the railcar.  Further examination of the drum revealed two cracks at the bottom, which were identified as the source of the leak.
column170: Shipper must ensure that proper blocking and bracing of containers is done as well as ensuring the condition of containers are worthy of transporting hazardous materials.

On April 4th, 2025, while loading and unloading a shipment of liquid drums at Veolia's 10-day in-transit facility, a Veolia employee picked up a drum of petroleum distillates using the drum gripper to weigh it. During this process, a co-worker noticed a small pinhole leak in the drum. The employees promptly covered the hole with a spill pad and tape to stop the leak, then cleaned up the spilled liquid on the floor using spill dry. The leaking drum was overpacked into a 951H2 container for continued transportation.

column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a punctured pail containing hazardous product, Vapor Retarder Primer VC. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 3-gallon release onto the wooden trailer floor in a 5’ x 5’ area as a result of a forklift puncture. The contractor applied oil dry to the release and overpacked the damaged leaking drum. The consignee accepted the rest of the undamaged/un-impacted freight. One 55-gallon DF containing the overpacked leaking pail was generated for waste disposal. One 55-gallon DF containing impacted oil dry and pallet pieces was generated for waste disposal. One 55-gallon DM containing impacted oil dry and pallet pieces was generated for waste disposal. XPO will manage all waste created from the incident. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

column63: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column169: On 04-10-2025 a CN mechanical performing an inbound inspection of train M-33891-09 observed vapor emitting from the valve area of TILX 112000.The employee notified the Dangerous Goods Team and made internal emergency notifications per the CN ERP.  The CN Dangerous Goods Officer upon arrival found vapor coming from the air valve. The blind flange was not applied, and the valve was cracked open. The liquid line also had the shipper supplied loading fitting still applied. The fitting did not have a cap on.  The air valve was closed, and the blind flange was reapplied. On the liquid line the shippers fitting was removed, and the blind flange was reapplied. The tank cars pressure plate was cleaned by the CN Dangerous Goods Team.

On 4/3/2025 at approximately 1330 hours, Dangerous Goods Administration received notification of undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of 2 fiberboard boxes, each contained multiple bottles of perfume.   AWB# 772715499316 had 22 bottles of perfume and AWB 772787929150 had 19 bottles of perfume.  Customs intercepted the shipment for further investigation, which confirmed the presence of the perfume.  Neither shipment was prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, as it did not display the required markings, labeling, packaging, or paperwork.  Customs has requested that the shipments be destroyed.

At 20:40 PM ET, Alyssa Estes with NMO contacted the call center to report a spill that occurred on the dock in Montgomery, AL. The spill consists of approximately half a gallon of Sure Klean 600, which released from 1-1-gallon plastic jug due to a forklift puncture during dock operations. The spill has impacted the dock floor only.  The call center will dispatch a contractor to assist with cleanup as this is a corrosive release. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately (1) 5-gallon jug of UN3264 Sure Klean 600 product released to dock floor due to forklift puncture. The contractors used absorbents to dry up the spill and sprayed with soda ash solution to neutralize it. The impacted pallet was wrapped and was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

During loading process, EQIS driver discovers drum on pallet with regulated waste material leaking from side, and that generator staff had installed locking ring upside down, and with inadequate ring gasket.  Approximate loss of product from packaging approx. .5 to 1 gallon.  Material cleaned up by staff, cleaning trailer floor and exterior of package.  Our driver re-installed the ring closure appropriately and monitored this package to point of delivery with no further loss of product. Minimal product loss was contained within small area of trailer floor and cleaned up by our staff with no release outside of trailer.
column170: We have assigned our driver to remedial training to help ensure issues like these are identified on the storage room floor and before failing package gets placed on board our vehicle.  We are also liaising with waste generator to ensure their staff understand packaging and closure requirements to inhibit a repeat.  Communication and training.

Hepaco was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 53ft-by-8ft area of the trailer floor and 10ft-by-10ft area of concrete and estimated that fifty (50) gallons of material were released due to forklift damaging one (1) poly tote. Hepaco personnel used Soda Ash to neutralize Hydrochloric acid. Contractor personnel deployed granular absorbents and absorbent pads to the affected areas. Hepaco personnel transferred the remaining product from the damaged drum to a new poly tote. The impacted absorbents were containerized into five (5) 55-gallon poly drums. Impacted PPE was containerized into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged tote was cut up and was put in one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The impacted plywood was put in one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged drums were staged onsite. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal

A warehouse associate loaded a trailer at the NAC Kent (WA) facility with a specific load configuration. The trailer contained thirty-three drums of Interplastic COR61-AA-458K DCPD Laminating Resin, two drums of INEOS Aropol K 1813-14 Resin, and one drum of Interplastic B-1565L-LHM Gel Coat. The drums were loaded first and positioned at the front of the trailer. Additionally, there were seventeen pallets of Ilium Composites fiberglass, which were double-stacked and loaded last.  The seventeen pallets of fiberglass were smaller than the pallets used for the metal drums. While transporting a fiberglass pallet with a forklift, the warehouse associate accidentally moved the pallet too far forward in the trailer. This misplacement caused two 55-gallon drums to become punctured, resulting in the contents of both drums spilling onto the wooden floor of the trailer.  Meanwhile, a local fire chief, traveling behind our tractor and trailer, noticed the resin leaking. He flagged down the truck driver and advised him to pull over. The truck driver then notified his supervisor, who subsequently informed me (Jerry Davis, VP Operational and Regulatory Affairs at NAC). In response, I contacted Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. for assistance.   Clean Harbors arrived at the scene approximately 90 minutes after the spill and initiated an initial cleanup. They removed the pallets from the trailer and identified two leaking drums. After cleaning the trailer on-site, Clean Harbors loaded it, and the NAC truck driver transported the trailer to Kent. Clean Harbors also applied a tarp over the soil area contaminated with polyester resin.  Below is a list of the waste debris generated during the initial cleanup.  1. (15) 55-gallon drums of contaminated soil 2. (5) 250-gallon totes of wash water 3. (2) 65-gallon overpack metal drums of debris   On April 14, a technician from Clean Harbors visited the site and collected six samples from the contaminated area, which were sent to a laboratory for analysis. The results of these tests are attached.  Clean Harbors returned on April 16 to remove approximately 20 cubic yards of contaminated soil. After excavation, they collected another set of six samples and sent those to the laboratory for additional analysis.  The second laboratory report indicated that sample number four contained high levels of styrene, a major component of polyester resin. This report was shared with Michael Warfel at the Washington Department of Ecology. He advised NAC to hire a geoengineering firm experienced with state cleanup requirements to prepare a report on any necessary further cleanup actions.  NAC notified the Department of Ecology on April 7, 2025.  The report number is 738088.  NAC also notified the Department of Transportation on April 8, 2025.  The report number is 25-1276.
column170: The warehouse associate's lack of attention and carelessness while loading the drums on the trailer with the forklift caused this spill. He has received forklift training annually for the past eight (8) years. This incident and the risks of handling smaller pallets were discussed with all operations managers, warehouse associates, and truck drivers.  ROOT CAUSE: Forklift operator error.

At 23:54 EDT on 4/3, XPO-BCA contacted ERTS to report a spill of about 2 cups of "Lithium Hydroxide Monohydrate" from a 50lb paper bag onto the trailer floor. The bag was punctured by a forklift at BCA. ERTS confirmed the product to be a regulated corrosive and will dispatch a contractor to assist. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed  approximately 1.5 cups of UN3110 Perkadox BCFF product released from (2) 55-pound boxes to the trailer floor due to improper loading. On April 7, 2025, at 1847, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Inway personnel in Conroe, TX regarding the release of FLP MC-130 Conc. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 330 gallons of FLP MC-130 Conc. (UN1993, 3, III) from (1) 330-gallon poly tote onto the trailer floor and soil. The release was reportedly due to a load shift during transit, impacting the trailer floor and a 30’ x 50’ area of soil surrounding the trailer. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The trailer floor was cleaned up with absorbents and the proper PPE. The top layer of impacted soil was removed, then the harder layer underneath was secured for future excavation. 200 gallons of product were recovered from the ground and placed in a tote for potential recycling. The impacted absorbents and removed soil were containerized in (1) roll-off container which was taken offsite by the contractor for proper disposal along with the empty 330-gallon tote and recovered 200 gallons of product.

Dayton Freight personnel observed approximately twelve (12) gallons of material released from one (1) 55-gallon poly drum due to a manufacturing defect at the bottom of the drum that resulted in the drum leaking. The released material impacted the concrete dock floor. Dayton Freight personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and gathered the spent material and containerized it into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged drum was containerized into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

column169: At 2041 EST, XSJ notified ERTS of a cargo release inside trailer #3178473. It was reported an unknown material was leaking from a 250-gallon IBC tote. The spill is actively leaking inside the trailer and breaking containment; the terminal has moved the trailer to the yard.   A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 50-gallon release onto the entire wooden trailer  floor and various areas onto the concrete beneath the trailer. The contractor applied oil dry to the release and  applied a spill diaper to the leaking metal tote. One 55-gallon DF containing the impacted absorbents was  generated. The Shipper will be sending a replacement metal tote to perform a tote transfer. XPO will manage  all waste created from the response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

column169: AT APPROXIMATELY 18:45 THE SUPERVISOR FROM THE IRREG SORTING AREA APPROACHED THE DMP CAGE AND INFORMED A RESPONDER THEY HAD A LEAKING BUCKET ON AN IRREG CART. AFTER DONNING PROPER PPE AND RETRIEVING A FULLY STOCKD SPILL CART, THE RESPONDER THEN HEADED TO THE SCENE OF THE SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL THE RESPONDER NOTICED A PLASTIC CLOSED HEAD 5 GALLON BUCKET LAYING ON ITS SIDE WITH A PUDDLE OF LIQUID ON THE FLOOR NEXT TO IT. AFTER REFERRING TO THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE RESPONDER ACTED ACCORDINGLY. THE BUCKET WAS THEN TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE DMP CAGE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. AFTER CLOSER INSPECTION IT WAS DETERMINED THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS A PUNCTURE HOLE TO THE BODY OF THE CONTAINER. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DMP DISPOSAL FLOW CHART THE LIQUID AND CONTAINER WERE ALL PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a punctured leaking poly tote containing hazardous product, Barquat MB-50. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 140-gallon release onto the wooden trailer floor, the concrete beneath the trailer, the asphalt parking lot, and the soil. The trailer floor was impacted in a 20’ x 8.5’ area and the concrete beneath the trailer, asphalt, and soil were impacted in a 100’ x 75’ area. The contractor neutralized the release and applied oil dry. A vac truck extracted approximately 2,700-gallons of impacted rainwater and containerized it into one vac box. Three 55-gallon DF’s containing the cut-up tote, impacted oil dry, and impacted PPE were also generated. ERTS will coordinate disposal of the vac box. XPO will manage the drum waste created from the response. No storm-drains or waterways were involved in this incident.

column169: The driver noticed material on the tire of his trailer during his pre-trip inspection. The driver immediately stopped the leak from the drum. A spill response contractor was called to the location of the trailer, since the driver did not have the equipment needed to remove the leaking drum from the trailer.  The spill contractor found the leaking drum, removed it from the trailer, placed the leaking drum into an overpack, and then cleaned up the material on the inside and outside of the trailer.  The overpack was placed back in the trailer.  A minimal amount of material, less than 1 gallon, was released below the trailer.  The rest of the material was contained to the inside of the trailer. Upon observation of the drum, it looks like there was a very small puncture in the side of the drum.

column169: On 04-05-2025 a CN mechanical performing an inbound inspection of train M-34241-05 observed frost on the protective housing of tank car # SHPX 222262 along with a strong Propane type odor in the area. The employee notified the Dangerous Goods Team and made internal emergency notifications per the CN ERP.  The CN Dangerous Goods Officer upon arrival and inspection found icing on the 2# B end liquid valve. It was found that the valve handle was not in the fully closed position. The plug was also found to be less than tool tight allowing product to leak out. The 2# Vapor valve was also found to be leaking due to the valve handle not being in the fully closed position and the securement plug was less than tool tight. Air monitoring readings on top of the car were below actionable levels with the highest LEL (Lower Explosive Limit) reading sitting at an 8%. PPE was FR Clothing and based on the Air monitoring readings on top of the car no raspatory protection was worn.  Both the 2" B end liquid valve and vapor valve were closed stopping the release. The plug was removed allowing the residual product to vent and the valve to thaw. The securement was confirmed with an air monitor which showed non detect. The securement plug was then installed

column169: On April 14, 2025, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN3109 was punctured and released approximately three (3) cups of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental Services (GES) to remediate the site. The crew identified the one (1) damaged 5-gallon jug of product, which was placed into its own 55-gallon vented poly drum for waste. The release had been cleaned by terminal personnel, and the jug of product had been patched and plugged. The spent absorbents were placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum that was placed into the terminal's dumpster. Crews inspected the dumpster and found that all impacted absorbents were successfully containerized in the one  (1) 55-gallon drum and had not released to the rest of the dumpster, so crews removed the 55-gallon drum. The impacted absorbents were transferred into one (1) new 55-gallon, vented poly drum, and the damaged drum was cut up with hand tools for waste. Crews utilized absorbent pads and cleaning agents to wipe down the impacted dock floor. One (1) 55-gallon vented poly drum of any spent absorbents, cleanup debris, and the cut-up drum was staged alongside the one (1) 55-gallon drum that contained the one (1) impacted jug.

column169: At 09:03 ET, XPO notified the Call Center of a cargo release at terminal XSF. It was reported that an unknown amount of an unknown hazard class 2.3 released from one compressed gas canister due to currently unknown reasons. The release impacted Trailer #3171296 which is located in the yard, close to Dock #38.   Contractor stated that there was condensation on the cylinders and some residual product in the cylinders. After speaking with the Shipper, they were informed that the cylinders shipped as empty, but that they do not bleed them empty, so residual is possible. Wally's team found 7 cylinders that weren't closed properly that could have contributed to the hissing that XPO was hearing. The contractor's dragar tubes did provide some detections low in the trailer and those readings will be provided to us, momentarily. They used simple green to clean the trailer floor. A crew member will be returning to the sire to overpack the PAIL of impacted absorbents and the contractor will be billing for the SCBA refills.
column173: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

An FRA inspector observed the smell of Ethanol from # UTLX 209125 from the manway cover while performing a regulatory compliance check at the CN Glenn Yard in Chicago, IL. The inspector notified the CN Dangerous Goods Officer who responded to the incident location. The CN Dangerous Goods Officer's inspection of tank car revealed vapor leaking from the gasket sealing surface between the manway nozzle and the manway cover plate indicating a possible gasket failure. This was confirmed by using a 4 gas meter. The manway cover was opened for inspection of the gasket. The gasket appeared to be dry rotted and was replaced. column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a leaking 55-gallon metal drum containing hazardous product, Leaded Race Fuel. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 55-gallons released onto the entire wooden trailer floor, the asphalt beneath the trailer in a 60’x10’ area, and a drain (catch basin) as a result of a forklift puncture. The contractor cleaned up the release using a vac truck and oil dry. One 85-gallon DF containing the empty damaged drum was generated for waste disposal along with three 55-gallon DM’s containing impacted absorbents, and 2,800-gallons of impacted water inside of the vac truck. XPO will manage the waste drums created from the response and ERTS will coordinate disposal of the vac truck liquids at a local third-party disposal site. No waterways or soil were involved in this incident.

column169: The truck moved over to the shoulder of the road to let a larger wideload truck pass.  The shoulder of the road gave way and the truck slid down the embankment and rolled over. The truck contained 2000 gallons of diesel fuel.  A small amount of fuel was leaking out of the vent valves on top of the truck tank.  When speaking to the responding officer and fire department, they said very little fuel had spilled. The fire department put floor dry down to soak up fuel that had reached the ground.  They also placed spill buckets down to catch any product that was stilling coming out of the vent.  The floor dry and top soil have been removed and placed in a container.  The truck was placed upright and remaining diesel fuel in the truck tank was transfered into another fuel truck.  Diesel fuel release was estimated at 35 minutes from time of incident to containment.
column170: Train drivers on using caution when movng large truck onto shoulder of the road.

column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding damaged leaking jerricans containing, Peraside (Organic Peroxide) and 05-pails with damaged lids containing, Sodium Hypochlorite. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 0.5-gallon release of hazardous product, Peraside (Organic Peroxide) onto the concrete dock floor in a 4’ x 2’ area as a result of a forklift puncture. Additionally, the contractor identified four 05-pails of Sodium Hypochlorite with broken lids. The Sodium Hypochlorite did not release, therefore there was no impact area. The contractor generated one 55-gallon DF containing two loose-packed jerricans of Peraside (Organic Peroxide) for waste disposal. The impacted debris and PPE from that clean-up was containerized and wetted inside of a separate 55-gallon DF for waste disposal. Two 55-gallon DF’s containing the four loose-packed 05-pails of Sodium Hypochlorite were generated for waste disposal. XPO will manage all waste created from the response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

column169: On 4/4/2025 at 11:15 EST, a World Fuel Services, Inc. (WFS) Cincinnati Tank Wagon driver was making a delivery to a 3,000-gallon aboveground storage tank (AST) located at Loveland Schools Bus Lot in Loveland, OH. During the delivery, the product started overfilling from the AST vent resulting in an uncontrol release of diesel fuel to the environment at 11:25 EST. The employee, after noticing the spill, ran to shut the pump off and then grabbed spill pads to mitigate the spill. The employee attempted to clean-up spill and contacted WFS Operations. WFS Operations contacted WFS HSE personnel to assist with the incident, spill clean-up, and investigation. The employee did not follow procedures and was not at the point of flow during delivery. The employee was distracted by being on their phone away from the delivery point. Truck camera footage showed two minutes, and thirty-five seconds went by until the employee noticed the release. The employee did not confirm ullage by sticking the tank. The release occurred because of human error. The weather on site that day was on and off again precipitation. This contributed to the spill discharging into the detention pond on site. The calculated release is 165 gallons of No. 2 diesel fuel based on reviewing the truck camera footage.   The spill impacted the parking lot, storm drain, and a 6,000 square foot detention basin/pond. The NRC was notified of the release on 4/4/25 at 18:00 EST. The Ohio EPA was notified of the release on 4/4/2025 at 18:15 EST. The spill was reported to Hamilton County EMA on 4/4/2025 at 18:30 EST. WFS and Ohio EPA met on-site on 4/8/2025 to determine clean-up plan for the detection pond. Ohio EPA approved WFS/HEPACO to treat the basin with in-situ bioremediation and monitoring the site by taking soil samples for VOCs readings until site is clean and no further action is required. Impacted vegetation (leaves/branches) on the ground were removed. Oil booms were placed at the storm drain’s discharge point and at the outfall of the detention pond. Oil booms are being inspected after precipitation events and replaced as needed. HEPACO/WFS will continue to monitor the in-situ bioremediation and inform the Ohio EPA of its progress.
column170: World Fuel Services, Inc. (WFS) reviews and investigates all incidents to determine root cause and what corrective actions need to be implemented to prevent any recurrences. The spill occurred because of a human error and the employee did not follow WFS tank wagon delivery procedures. The WFS driver did not follow procedures by properly confirming tank ullage prior to delivery. The WFS driver did not stick the tank for a tank level reading. And the WFS employee was not at the point of flow and talking on their cellphone causing a distraction during delivery. These errors resulted in an overfill and release to the environment. WFS Operations personnel will be brief on the incident and retrained on delivery procedures.

A shipment was moved from Veolia's Mooresville 10-day facility to Veolia's Creedmoor facility using a Freehold Cartage Inc trailer. Upon unloading the following morning, a material handler noticed a pallet of triple-stacked and shrink-wrapped carboys had shifted. Two of the carboys were off the pallet and leaning against another drum. One of the carboy drum containers had a loose cap, resulting in less than a pint of material spilling onto the trailer floor. The spill was cleaned up, the cap was tightened, and all other caps were checked before the pallet was shrink-wrapped once more for continued transportation to the final destination facility.
column170: The spill occurred due to inadequate load securement prior to shipping. The shrink wrap failed to prevent the pallet from shifting during transit from Mooresville to Creedmoor. The cap on the 051H1DF carboy container either became loose during transit or was not properly secured before leaving the facility. The issue of improper load securement and closure instructions, including proper cap and bung tightening, has been addressed in employee training. A Transportation Compliance Alert has been issued to remind employees to complete and review the Veolia Hazmat Checklist before transporting materials on public roads. Drivers are strongly advised to contact their local manager with any compliance questions or concerns prior to beginning transportation.

column43: CARTRIDGES FOR WEAPONS, INERT PROJECTILE OR CARTRIDGES, SMALL ARMS
column169: On 4/16/2025 at approximately 1745, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 832024 at the station location in Roseville, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of one fiberboard box that contained two stuffed teddy bears and other Easter-themed decorations.  The shipment was discovered by the K-9 unit during the location's screening procedure.  Further investigation resulted in the discovery of a disassembled AR-15 rifle and a loaded magazine cartridge that was found inside one of the teddy bears. The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, missing the required markings, labeling, packaging, and paperwork.  The shipment is being held, pending an investigation by the FAA.

column43: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column169: On 4/14/2025 at approximately 1745, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 5105681 at the station location in Kansas City, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of two cans of paint packaged in a fiberboard box.  The shipment was discovered emitting a strong odor at the facility.  Further investigation revealed that paint had spilled inside of its inner packaging and contained. The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, missing the required markings, labeling, packaging and paperwork.  The shipment is being held, pending an investigation by the FAA. All measurements mentioned in this report are estimated due to the missing information.
